revision.text:
{{Infobox book | name = A Constructive Survey of Upanishadic Philosophy | image = | caption = | author = [[Ramachandra Dattatrya Ranade]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = India | language = English | series = | subject = Philosophy | genre = Vedanta | published = 1926 (Oriental Books Agency, [[Pune]]) | media_type = Print | pages = | awards = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{Hinduism}} '''''A Constructive Survey of Upanishadic Philosophy''''' is a book by [[Ramachandra Dattatrya Ranade]], also known as Gurudev Ranade, who was an eminent scholar of the [[Upanishads]] who specialised in [[Greek philosophy]] and emphasized the centrality of a psychological approach as opposed to a theological approach for the proper understanding of the [[Brahman|Ultimate Reality]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Nalini Bhushan |author2=Jay L. Garfield |title=Indian Philosophy in English: From Renaissance to Independence |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ebo8NpbpNk0C&pg=PA245 |year=2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-991128-8 |page=245}}</ref> The book was first published in 1926 by Oriental Books Agency, [[Pune]], under the patronage of Sir Parashuramarao Bhausaheb, Raja of [[Jamkhandi State|Jamkhandi]]. It was later republished by [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]], [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Jashan P. Vaswani |title=Sketches of Saints Known and Unknown |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0JPT6s07l-IC&pg=PA199 |year=2008 |publisher=Sterling Paperbacks Ltd. |isbn=978-81-207-3998-7 |pages=197–202 |location=New Delhi}}</ref>
Ranade wrote the book on the basis of his various lectures on Upanishads and the [[Bhagavad Gita]] that were delivered in 1915. In that year, inspired by a lecture of Sir Ramakrishna Gopal Bhandarkar, he had first conceived the idea of a presentation of Upanishadic philosophy in terms of modern thought. He took into consideration of the place of the Upanishads in Indian philosophy, and examined the opinions of the Orientalists with a view to put into hand of the Orientalists and those interested a new method for treating the problems of Indian philosophy, and into the hands of European philosophers a new material for exercising their intellects on, to serve the main intended spiritual purpose. He employed "the method of construction through a systematic exposition of all the problems that emerge from the discussion of Upanishadic thought in their manifold bearings".<ref>{{cite book |author=R.D.Ranade |title=Preface to A Constructive Survey of Upanishadic Philosophy |url=https://books.google.com/?id=sE8pAAAAYAAJ| edition = 1968 |year=1968 |publisher=Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan |pages=vii-xix |location=Mumbai}}</ref> The work is broadly divided into seven chapters. First he deals with the background of Upanishadic Speculation, then with the development of Upanishadic Cosmogony. He discusses the varieties of psychological reflection and the roots of later philosophies, before taking up the problem of the Ultimate Reality in the Upanishads. He covers the ethics of the Upanishads, and finally the intimation of self-realisation. It is a wide-ranging study<ref>{{cite book |last=Phillips |first=Stephen |title=Aurobindo's Philosophy of Brahman |url=https://books.google.com/?id=H9gUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA58 |year=1986 |publisher=Brill Archive |isbn=90-04-07765-0 |page=58}}</ref> that through Jnanamarga leads to the inference that dualism or pluralism is only apparent.<ref>{{cite book |last=Vitsaxis |first=Vassilis |title=Thought and Faith |url=https://books.google.com/?id=52b-A2l7QbwC&pg=PA89 |year=2009 |publisher=Somerset Hall Press |isbn=978-1-935244-05-9 |page=89}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Klaus K. Klostermaier | authorlink = Klaus Klostermaier |title=A Survey of Hinduism |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ltn3OuF_i4sC&pg=PA461 |year=1989 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=978-0-88706-807-2 |page=461}}</ref> Ranade provides an exhaustive bibliography that classifies the secondary books on Upanishads under three basic heads: as histories of literature, histories of religion and histories of philosophies.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sharma |first=Shubhra |title=Life in the Upanishads |url=https://books.google.com/?id=HVUptup6ZnEC&pg=PA21 |year=1985 |publisher=Abhinav Publications |isbn=978-81-7017-202-4 |page=21}}</ref> He has, as expected, mentioned about the creation of cosmos by two methods i.e. from life and from lifeless matter.<ref>{{cite book |author=Arvind Savant |title=Discovery of God |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Hqro8rrN-3MC&pg=PA189 |year=2011 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=978-1-4568-4518-6 |page=189}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref>
